-- Telenor’s Skogen Lund to Head Norway’s Biggest Business Group
-- B y   M i k a e l   H o l t e r
-- 2012-09-10T08:42:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-09-10/telenor-s-skogen-lund-to-head-norway-s-biggest-business-group.html
Telenor ASA executive Kristin Skogen Lund was named director general of the Confederation of
Norwegian Enterprise, putting her in charge of lobbying for and
securing business interests in the Nordic country.  The 46-year-old will replace John G. Bernander as of Nov.
1,  Norway ’s largest business group, known as NHO, said today in
a statement from Oslo. She will resign as head of Telenor’s
digital services and broadcast, the company said in a statement.
She joined the Nordic region’s biggest phone operator as
executive vice president in March 2010.  “The reason I’m joining NHO is because it presents a
unique and exciting opportunity in an organization I know
well,” Skogen Lund, who has been president of the group since
April 2010, said in the statement. NHO represents 21,000
Norwegian companies.  The former director general of Aftenposten, Norway’s
biggest daily newspaper, was named Norway’s most powerful woman
by Norwegian fortnightly business magazine Kapital last year. In
2010, she was named the 38th most powerful woman in business by
Fortune Magazine  “We know Kristin as a dynamic leader with a strong
interest in society at large, making her the ideal candidate to
head NHO,” Telenor Chief Executive Officer Jon Fredrik Baksaas
said in a statement.  Bernander, the group’s current head, will become chief
executive of Viking Heat Engines AS as of Sept. 13.  To contact the reporter on this story:
